SIMPLE: harmonize
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Harmonize
<hw>Har"mo*nize</hw> <pr>(h⟦aum⟧r"m⟦osl⟧*n⟦imac⟧z)</pr>, <pos>v.
i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Harmonized</conjf>
<pr>(-n⟦imac⟧zd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Harmonizing</conjf> <pr>(-n⟦imac⟧"z⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph>
<ety>[Cf. F. <ets>harmoniser</ets>. ]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To agree in
action, adaptation, or effect on the mind; to agree in sense or purport;
<as>as, the parts of a mechanism <ex>harmonize</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be in peace and friendship, as individuals,
families, or public organizations.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To agree in vocal or musical effect; to form a
concord; <as>as, the tones <ex>harmonize</ex> perfectly</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Harmonize</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Harmonize
<hw>Har"mo*nize</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To adjust in fit
proportions; to cause to agree; to show the agreement of; to reconcile
the apparent contradiction of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>To accompany with harmony; to
provide with parts, as an air, or melody.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Harmonizer</ent>⟦br⟧
